'''Hex missiles''' were projectile [[Missile/Legends|missiles]] containing a special warhead armed with the chemical weapon [[Trihexalon]], also known as Dragon's Breath. [[Captain/Legends|Captain]] [[Cavik Toth]] of [[Sabaoth Squadron/Legends|Sabaoth Squadron]] deployed Hex missiles against the natives of [[Maramere]] prior to the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]].

Captain Toth had Hex weapons forged in the foundry on [[Nod Kartha]], and ordered [[Lieutenant/Legends|Lieutenant]] [[Bella (Twi'lek)|Bella]] to test them against the [[Point Modie]] settlement on Maramere.
{{Gamemechanics}}
Hex missiles rained down upon the island from orbit, though fortunately for the [[Mere]] inhabitants, [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Adi Gallia/Legends|Adi Gallia]], in her [[Delta-7 Aethersprite-class light interceptor/Legends|Delta-7 starfighter]], was able to destroy them before they reached Point Modie. Her [[Pirate/Legends|pirate]] ally [[Nym/Legends|Nym]] later led the [[Lok Revenants/Legends|strike]] [[Mere Resistance|force]] that [[Battle of Nod Kartha|destroyed]] the factory on Nod Kartha.

With his last reserves of Hex missiles, Toth launched an attack on the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]] forces [[First Battle of Geonosis/Legends|fighting]] on [[Geonosis/Legends|Geonosis]], sending [[Hex Deployer]]s and [[Hex Bomber|bombers]] towards the surface. Once more, Master Gallia was able to intercept and destroy all missiles launched at Geonosis, before [[Starfighter combat/Legends|eliminating Toth]] and his [[Sabaoth destroyer|flagship]].
{{Endgame}}

==Behind the scenes==
Destroying all Hex missiles is not necessary for victory in the missions in which these weapons appear in the [[Star Wars video games|video game]] ''[[Star Wars: Jedi Starfighter]]''.

